"{\"uid\": \"si.com-olympics-what-to-what-paris-olympics-august-6-gabby-thomas-200-meter-final\", \"text\": \"It\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Day 11 of the Olympics, so you probably have your routine down by now. Hopefully you\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ve been checking out this post every day, which means you know the drill. My daily watch guide is here to help you know what events need to be on your screen(s).  Hopefully you\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ve also subscribed toSports Illustrated\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Daily Rings, my daily podcast where Dan Gartland and I recap as much as we possibly can every single day. New episodes have been published every night before NBC\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s prime-time coverage is even over. You can also see clips of the podcast on YouTube (likeour segment Monday night about Mondo Duplantis).  Here\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s what I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ll be watching Tuesday, August 6.  This is not a comprehensive list;visit Olympics.comfor a full schedule. All events will stream live on Peacock. I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ll also be tweeting out a schedule of medal events, Team USA games and other favorites each day.  My Day 11 Olympics viewing guide! Getting smaller as U.S. teams get knocked out, but the number of medal events will go back up after Tuesday#Paris2024pic.twitter.com/n0srmuykCC  There seems to be another big event every day on the track, and now it\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s time for the women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s 200 meters. Team USA\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Gabby Thomas won bronze in Tokyo and is now the favorite, but don\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t forget about St. Lucia\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Julien Alfred, who won the 100 and will now go for the double.  Another race getting a lot of hype is the men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s 1500 meters. There is a fun rivalry between the Tokyo Olympic champ, Jakob Ingebrigtsen of Norway, and the reigning world champ, Great Britain\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Josh Kerr. This is going to be an entertaining race.  The track finals start at 1:35 p.m. ET and also include medal events in the women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s hammer throw, men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s long jump and women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s 3000-meter steeplechase.\\u00c2  Wrestling began Monday, and we\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ll see the first medals handed out Tuesday. We knew coming into the Olympics that Amit Elor was one of Team USA\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s best chances at a gold medal in wrestling, and her weight class was up on the first day.  She won her first three matches in dominating fashion and will be in the finals of the women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s 68-kg freestyle competition, which starts at 12:15 p.m. ET. But her gold medal match will be the 15th bout on that mat, so it\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s tough to give an exact start time.  I haven\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t brought up handball very much in this space, but it\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s always a fan favorite. They are now out of group play and into the knockout rounds. All four women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s quarterfinals will be on Tuesday, then the four men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s games will be on Friday.  Games are a full hour and they\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ll be running throughout the day. So now is a perfect time to pick a team and hop on a bandwagon. Every team still alive is three wins from a gold medal.  Now that sports are transitioning into knockout stages, there is a serious lineup of big games for U.S. teams:  Loading recommendations... Please wait while we load personalized content recommendations  Mitch Goldich is a senior editor for Sports Illustrated, mostly focused on the NFL. He has also covered the Olympics extensively and written on a variety of sports since joining SI in 2014. His work has been published by The New York Times, Baseball Prospectus and Food & Wine, among other outlets. Goldich has a bachelor\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s in journalism from Lehigh University and a master\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s in journalism from the Medill School at Northwestern University. He is a Philly native, now living in Boston, and he invented and popularized the octopus, when the same player scores a touchdown and the ensuing two-point conversion.  \\u00c2\\u00a9 2026ABG-SI LLC-SPORTS ILLUSTRATED IS A REGISTERED TRADEMARK OF ABG-SI LLC. - All Rights Reserved. The content on this site is for entertainment and educational purposes only. Betting and gambling content is intended for individuals 21+ and is based on individual commentators' opinions and not that of Sports Illustrated or its affiliates, licensees and related brands. All picks and predictions are suggestions only and not a guarantee of success or profit. If you or someone you know has a gambling problem, crisis counseling and referral services can be accessed by calling 1-800-GAMBLER.\"}"